AUSTIN, Texas (AP) — Texas shooting guard Andrew Jones, whose college basketball career was interrupted for nearly two years by leukemia, has announced he will skip a final season with the Longhorns and turn pro.Jones ranks ninth in scoring in program history with 1,620 points. He announced his decision to enter the NBA draft in a statement posted Sunday night on social media.“We have shared every emotion possible together and I will always cherish the experience I had with you all,” Jones said. “As I officially enter my name into the 2022 NBA draft, I am excited and most importantly ready for this next chapter of life.”Jones considered turning pro after his freshman season but opted to return to Texas for the 2017-2018 season. But just a few games into his sophomore season, Jones was sidelined with  leukemia that left him fighting for his life.ADVERTISEMENTHe posted several short videos of himself as he fought  through treatment and recovery, including one showing him standing still and trying to shoot a basketball into a hoop barely taller than he was.College basketballTexas guard Jones, who fought leukemia, to enter NBA draftWeekend Sports in BriefMaryland women add Vanderbilt's Alexander as grad transferFlorida's Johnson joins transfer portal, hopes to play againHe finally returned to the court full-time in the 2019-2020 season, when he averaged 11.5 points and was named the Big 12′s Male Sportsperson of the Year.The NBA draft is June 23.___More AP college basketball: https://apnews.com/hub/college-basketball and https://apnews.com/hub/ap-top-25-college-basketball-poll and https://twitter.com/AP_Top25